@*
    ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    BnModal — Phase 7.4 (design decisions 1-4), authored in .razor.

    THE FIRST OVERLAY SURFACE. Emits the `modal` element → NodeType 11 — an
    overlay in the EXISTING root, NOT a native dialog window (decision 1:
    a Dialog/presented-VC means a second Yoga root, a second calculate pass,
    a second frame-application surface — and a window that OWNS its own
    dismissal, the state-owner violation the 7.3 picker precedent forbids).
    Shell-side (Gates 2/3) a `modal` node materializes as TWO pieces:

      • the ANCHOR — a 0-sized `position:absolute` view at the modal's WIRE
        position, so sibling insert indices never skew (the THIRD normative
        index-mapping rule, after the text collapse and the scroll content
        node: the modal's wire child at index i is the OVERLAY's child at
        index i);
      • the OVERLAY — a full-root container attached LAST at the host root,
        painted with `scrimColor`; the modal's wire children parent into it
        (the containerFor/scrollContents redirection pattern). Stacking is
        creation order; a re-shown modal is a re-created one and lands on
        top. RemoveNode(modalId) purges BOTH subtrees (NOT the scroll
        shape — the overlay is not a descendant of the anchor).

    ── THE WIRE (what .NET puts on it — Gate 1's half) ──────────────────────
      • `scrimColor` prop — ALWAYS emitted (the BnInput posture: the host
        prop exists from mount, no shell-side default two platforms would
        have to keep equal). Default #80000000. A PROP, not a style —
        deliberately: SetStyle on a `modal` node is diagnosed-and-ignored on
        both shells (every style would land on the anchor or the overlay,
        neither of which the author owns), and this component's surface
        cannot emit one.
      • `click` on the MODAL element — THE DISMISSAL-REQUEST WIRE, always
        attached. The shells dispatch it for a tap that lands on the SCRIM
        VIEW ITSELF (never a descendant — decision 4's normative rule) and,
        on Android, for the hardware back with this modal topmost
        (decision 3). Same wire, platform-appropriate trigger.
      • ONE wire child — the CONTENT BOX, a plain view carrying the
        DECLARED ContentWidth/ContentHeight/Padding/BackgroundColor (the
        BnScroll forwarding precedent); ChildContent renders inside it. The
        box swallows its own taps via a real no-op `click` attach (the RN
        inner-Touchable pattern): on Android a non-clickable child's tap
        falls THROUGH to the scrim, so the box being clickable is what makes
        a content tap NOT a dismissal — and that dispatch is real, the
        device counters account for it.

    ── HIDE UNMOUNTS; .NET OWNS VISIBILITY (decision 2) ─────────────────────
    Internally `@if (Visible)`: false means ZERO wire presence, and the whole
    overlay subtree leaves as ONE RemoveNodePatch (the disposal shape 7.2's
    removes-first fix hardened). Dismissal — scrim tap, Android back, the
    app's own button — is a REQUEST: this component invokes
    VisibleChanged(false) and changes nothing itself. A parent that ignores
    it keeps the modal open — correct; no self-closing state exists anywhere
    in the shell. A dismissal that races a second one is absorbed by
    construction: Visible is already false, the handler is stale (at-most-
    once delivery), nothing moves. Consequence, stated once: state inside
    ChildContent does NOT survive hide unless bound — the 7.2 eviction rule
    verbatim (an app that wants it binds it, exactly as on the web).
    ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
*@
@if (Visible)
{
    <modal scrimColor="@(ScrimColor ?? DefaultScrimColor)" @onclick="HandleDismissRequest">
        <div backgroundColor="@BackgroundColor"
             padding="@Padding.ToStyleValue()"
             width="@ContentWidth"
             height="@ContentHeight"
             @onclick="SwallowContentBoxTap">
            @ChildContent
        </div>
    </modal>
}

@code {
    /// <summary>Whether the modal is mounted. False = ZERO wire presence
    /// (hide is unmount — one RemoveNodePatch for the whole subtree). .NET
    /// owns this; the shell only ever REQUESTS a change via
    /// <see cref="VisibleChanged"/>.</summary>
    [Parameter] public bool Visible { get; set; }

    /// <summary>Raised with <c>false</c> on every dismissal request (scrim
    /// tap; Android back with this modal topmost) — the write-back half of
    /// the <c>@bind-Visible</c> pair. A parent that ignores it keeps the
    /// modal open.</summary>
    [Parameter] public EventCallback<bool> VisibleChanged { get; set; }

    /// <summary>The modal's content — rendered inside the content box.
    /// State in here does NOT survive hide unless bound (hide is unmount;
    /// the 7.2 eviction rule).</summary>
    [Parameter] public RenderFragment? ChildContent { get; set; }

    /// <summary>The scrim colour used when you do not set one: a half-opaque
    /// black. Binding <see cref="ScrimColor"/> to null falls back to this rather
    /// than leaving the scrim unpainted.</summary>
    public const string DefaultScrimColor = "#80000000";

    /// <summary>The colour painted over the page behind the content box, as a
    /// hex string with alpha. Null falls back to
    /// <see cref="DefaultScrimColor"/>, so the scrim is never accidentally
    /// invisible.</summary>
    [Parameter] public string? ScrimColor { get; set; } = DefaultScrimColor;

    // ── The content box's declared surface (the BnScroll forwarding
    //    precedent — these style the BOX, which the author owns; the modal
    //    node itself carries NO styles, by design) ──────────────────────────

    /// <summary>The content box's declared width, e.g. <c>"280"</c>.
    /// Null = auto (the box sizes to its content).</summary>
    [Parameter] public string? ContentWidth { get; set; }

    /// <summary>The content box's declared height, e.g. <c>"180"</c>.
    /// Null = auto.</summary>
    [Parameter] public string? ContentHeight { get; set; }

    /// <inheritdoc cref="BnView.Padding"/>
    [Parameter] public float? Padding { get; set; }

    /// <inheritdoc cref="BnView.BackgroundColor"/>
    [Parameter] public string? BackgroundColor { get; set; }

    /// <summary>The dismissal REQUEST (decision 2): re-sync the bound state;
    /// change nothing here. Visible flips only if the parent writes it
    /// back.</summary>
    private Task HandleDismissRequest()
        => VisibleChanged.InvokeAsync(false);

    /// <summary>The content-box swallow (decision 4): a REAL handler that
    /// moves nothing, so on Android a content tap stops at the box instead
    /// of falling through to the scrim. The dispatch is real — the device
    /// counters account for it.</summary>
    private static Task SwallowContentBoxTap()
        => Task.CompletedTask;
}
